Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Feeling like I missed asking something
Exam1_Recommendation:
1. COVID PCR test
2. Basic labs (CBC, BMP) and follow-up
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: Uncertainty with what might be going on
Exam2_Recommendation: 1. Increase metformin 2. Consider starting statin 3. Follow up on lab work, additional labwork if needed 4. Return in 3 months for inperson visit with exam

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Patient wanted to discuss everything at this visit and do a "General checkup" in addition to a problem-based visit (and one of his problems could potentially be cancer)
Exam1_Recommendation:
covid nasopharyngeal swab
referral to GI for colonoscopy
f/u health maintenance visit
return precautions discussed (worsening dyspnea, syncope, chest pain, etc.)
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: Worrying about pt's mental health
Exam2_Recommendation: Lab work (CBC, CMP, A1c, UA, microalbumin); pt will set reminders to take medications; follow-up in 2 weeks (will reassess mental health then, too, probably with GAD 7 and PHQ 9 as well)

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Unsure of how to evaluate or treat patients' fatigue
Exam1_Recommendation: 1) set alarm to take medications every day and start using a pill box to organize medications and help with adherence. Referral to pharmacy to assist with this. 2) diet and lifestyle modifications. 3) plan to check in again in 3 months, if A1c still increasing and/or patient is still symptomatic, can increase med doses. Discussed option to see PT for stiffness, pt declined, as this was less important to him than his A1c
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: Patient didn't know where to get tested and I didn't know off the top of my head where the closest testing site was
Exam2_Recommendation: 1) get a covid test. 2) Recommend girlfriend also gets a covid test. 3) symptomatic treatment, eg tylenol for fever. 4) if symptoms get worse (dyspnea, worsening cough or fever, headache, etc) call back or go to ED.

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: I was unsure of what was going on with his symptoms and trying to come up with a plan on how best to help the patient.
Exam1_Recommendation:
Administer PHQ-9 and GAD-7.
Increase Metformin.
Dietary counseling.
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: Being worried about fitting everything in, deciding to focus on most important concern for today.
Exam2_Recommendation: COVID-19 test, CBC, BMP, Lipid panel, follow up within the next week for full history and physical to establish care (depending on covid test results).

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Unsure how to proceed further as far as my questioning goes. Not sure if I should continue evaluating him medically or focus on the isolated issue he is presenting with.
Exam1_Recommendation:
1. COVID test
2. OTC medications for supportive therapy
3. F/u appt in office to evaluate if he is improving then also discuss preventative health measures
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: I was worried I was going to have to start calculating specific changes to his insulin regimen.
Exam2_Recommendation: 1. Clinical Pharm follow up to adjust insulin/meds. 2. f/u appt where we evaluate those changes and discuss other things to explore if those changes don't work

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Feeling like I missed asking something
Exam1_Recommendation:
1. COVID PCR test
2. Basic labs (CBC, BMP) and follow-up
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: Uncertainty with what might be going on
Exam2_Recommendation: 1. Increase metformin 2. Consider starting statin 3. Follow up on lab work, additional labwork if needed 4. Return in 3 months for inperson visit with exam

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: It's been awhile since I have thought about questions about diabetes, so I got a little nervous when I ran out of questions to ask when I wanted to collect a full history.
Exam1_Recommendation:
'- Order A1c, CBC (sodium, plasma and urine osmolarity)
- Diabetic foot exam
- I wasn't really sure what his dose of meds were, but I'd like to review that with my attending and see if we should increase the dose
- water deprivation test
- diet and exercise education.
- let pt know if condition worsens, then please go to ER.
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: I really wish this was an inperson visit as I feel like this gentleman probably would have benefitted a lot from a gen assessemnt of his health.
Exam2_Recommendation: '- order covid test, if this was in person, I'd do cardiac and pulm exam. At this time, I don't think he needs to the ER as he sounds pretty stable. After the covid test, things will be more clear and how to manage him whether that's antibiotics or symptomatic care. But I'd defintely want him to schedule an appointment with the office for a general physical as I felt like there could be other things to talk about his health. Encourage pt to quarantine at this time, and drink plenty of fluids.

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: I was thinking about how I don't know what is going wrong with the patient. I was worrying about letting him down and not being a good enough physician..
Exam1_Recommendation:
1. in person visit for physical exam about his weakness
2. lab work up: A1C, lipids
3. potential imaging of spine, head based on physical exam.
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: when I found myself talking over the patient and not hearing what he was saying because the video cut off audio when both people are talking.
Exam2_Recommendation: 1. stool (FIT test) and blood (cholesterol, kidney function) samples, covid test  2. in person physical exam, blood pressure check

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: pt repeating their fatigue, trying to create a large Ddx to capture any red flags and common Sx
Exam1_Recommendation:
1. increased diet and exersize
2. referral to nutrition
3. 2 week check of blood sugar log
4. increase metformin to 500 BID
5. routine labs Chem7 + creatine
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: not knowing if there was another hidden reason for Tom to be coming in, ie used excuse of cold to be brought in for STD, also trying to build a ddx on such bland symptoms
Exam2_Recommendation: 1. covid test 2. covid vaccine, 3 schedule other routine vaccinations (pneumo/shingx/etc) 4. CMP + sugars, return in 1 year

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Asking about patient's mood and how it has been affecting his life
Exam1_Recommendation:
1. Increased exercise (will try walking with older grandkids)
2. Discuss dietary referral with wife since she does the cooking
3. Will continue to monitor mood (anhedonia specifically) and f/u with PHQ-9 at next visit
4. Labs including CBC and TSH at his convenience
5. HgA1c before next DM f/u in 3 months
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: Asking about symptoms, trying to get more information when Tom was providing shorter answers
Exam2_Recommendation: 1. Covid test 2. Symptomatic management (sudafed/mucinex and/or tylenol) 3. F/u schedule an annual physical in person for lab work and physical exam

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Negotiating with the patient around his soda use, when he mentioned he felt like past providers were talking down with him.
Exam1_Recommendation: 1. Seeing patient in one month to recheck blood sugar and fatigue 2. Working with patient on plan to cut back sugar (soda, then coffee added sugar) 3. Considering medication changes or further workup if interventions are unsuccessful in managing blood sugar.
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: Discussing soda (didn't want to make thepatient feel guilty) and when he brought up feeling like past providers talked down to him.
Exam2_Recommendation: 1. Seeing patient in one month to follow up on blood sugar 2. Working with him to reduce soda in diet, and maybe added sugar in coffee 3. Considering further labs and workup if blood sugar is not improving or fatigue is worsening.

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Discussion about COVID-19 infection possibility
Exam1_Recommendation: Most likely viral infection given type of symptoms and duration of symptoms with low concern for COPD exacerbation given lack of history and diagnostic criteria. COVID infection possible given current community rates but risk factors low. First step, COVID-19 drive through testing + isolation until test results back. Second step, if COVID test negative, set up for COVID-19 vaccination series. In interval, supportive treatment.
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: was waivering about HHNS for a short time
Exam2_Recommendation: Suspect fatigue is likely related to blood blood sugar control. Differential also included occult bleeding (did not screen for) and unspecified malignancy. Plan for in person visit to review age appropriate screening, screen for occult blood loss, physical exam, motivational interviewing, and labs.

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: Trying to identify the source of the issue
Exam1_Recommendation:
1) increase metformin to 1000mg in the morning, and continue 500mg in the evening
2) take blood sugars daily 
3) return in two weeks, review blood glucose readings and other symptoms and adjust meds accordingly
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: trying to figure out what was going on
Exam2_Recommendation: 1) continue dayquil as needed 2) monitor symptoms, visit ED if symptoms worsen or acutely concerning (warning signs discussed with pt) 3) get covid test 4) f/u in a few weeks for full physical and well check

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: completed initial part of HPI, trying to decide what to do next
Exam1_Recommendation:
1. covid test
2. referral for GI/colonoscopy
3. covid vaccine
4. yearly labs: cbc, cmp, lipids, tsh, a1c
Exam2_Stress_Occurance: trying to decide what else to ask patient
Exam2_Recommendation: 1. physical exam including neuro exam of lower extremities, 2. increase metformin to 1000mg BID, 3. basic labs cbc, cmp, tsh, 4. return visit in 2wks

Exam1_Stress_Occurance: I felt like I was talking too much and not letting him speak, and that we were going over alotted time.
Exam1_Recommendation: Get labs: HA1c, cbc, cmp, vit D, lipid panel, tsh, t4. Getting vitals would be helpful at his lab appointment, specifically his blood pressure and weight to calculate BMI. Check blood sugar level when experiencing fatigue in the afternoons and tell us the number at the next visit. 2. Start Rosuvastatin 20mg. 3. Schedule in-person clinic visit in 1 month to get labs, Pneumococcal vaccine, do physical exam, talk about diet and exercise, assess impact of medication changes, and talk about colorectal cancer screening. 3. Referral to opthalmology for annual diabetic retinal exam. 4. Think about making a possible change to diet to introduce more plant-based foods: for example eating a salad one day a week from McDonald's rather than a burger. 5. Think about increasing number of weekly walks to approach a goal of 5 days a week of 30 minutes of moderately strenuous exercise.
